Gemini said
Since you're running Arch with Hyprland, Ghostty, and tmux, you clearly value a high-performance, terminal-centric workflow. Transitioning from the VSCode/Browser Jupyter experience to Neovim requires a shift in mindset: you move away from "all-in-one" GUI cells toward a decoupled "Editor + REPL" model.

As of 2026, there isn't a single "silver bullet" that perfectly clones the VSCode UI, but there are three powerful workflows that achieve the same (or better) productivity.

1. The Modern Interactive Powerhouse: Molten.nvim
If you want the visual feedback of VSCode (plots and images appearing inside your editor), Molten.nvim is the spiritual successor to the famous Magma.nvim.

How it works: It connects to a running Jupyter kernel. You write code in a standard .py or .ipynb file, send a "cell" to Molten, and it displays the output (text or images) in a floating window or as virtual text.

The "Secret Sauce": Since you use Ghostty, you have native Sixel or Kitty Graphics Protocol support. Molten can use these to render actual plots (Matplotlib, Plotly) directly inside your terminal.

Setup Tip: Pair it with image.nvim to handle the rendering of those high-res plots.

2. The Data Science Professional: Quarto-nvim
If you want a more structured "Notebook" feel that handles Markdown and Code blocks like a .ipynb file does, Quarto is currently the gold standard for Neovim.

Features: It allows you to use .qmd (Quarto) or .ipynb files. It provides cell-specific completion (via otter.nvim), meaning you get full LSP support even inside a markdown code block.

VSCode-like feel: It has commands to "Run Cell," "Run Above," etc. It usually pipes output to a side tmux pane or a Neovim terminal buffer.

Workflow: You get the benefits of a plain-text file (version control friendly) with the execution power of a notebook.

3. The Minimalist "Vim-Way": Jupytext + Iron.nvim
If you hate the JSON mess of .ipynb files and want to treat everything like pure Python:

Jupytext: Use this to transparently open .ipynb files as formatted Python scripts (using # %% to mark cells). When you save, it syncs back to the notebook format.

Iron.nvim: This is a high-performance REPL manager. You define "cells" with comments, and hit a keybind to send that chunk to a hidden or split terminal running IPython.

