Gemini said
It is absolutely an interim stage. You’ve hit on the central "friction point" of modern terminal development. We are currently in the middle of a transition from the legacy grid-of-text terminal to the modern graphical terminal.

While we aren't at "seamless" yet, the next 12–24 months look like the period where these disparate hacks finally coalesce into a standard. Here is why it feels "interim" and what is changing:

1. The Terminal Protocol War is ending
For decades, terminals could only display text. If you wanted an image, you had to use hacks like Sixel (from the 1980s).

The Interim State: Currently, we have three competing ways to show a plot: Sixel, the Kitty Graphics Protocol, and ITerm2's protocol. Neovim plugins have to write specific code for each.

The Improvement: Ghostty and Kitty have effectively "won" the mindshare of power users. Because Ghostty (your terminal) supports the Kitty protocol natively and is becoming the de-facto standard for Arch/Hyprland users, plugin developers are finally focusing on one high-performance standard rather than chasing five legacy ones.

2. Neovim is becoming "Graphics Aware"
Until very recently, Neovim didn't actually know what an "image" was; it just knew "empty space where a plugin is drawing something."

The Interim State: If you scroll your text in Neovim, the image often "lags" behind or stays pinned to the screen while the text moves under it. It feels brittle because the editor and the terminal aren't talking to each other about the image's position.

The Improvement: Neovim's core team is working on better external UI and grid-mapping protocols. By late 2026, expect "floating windows" to have native properties for handling graphical attachments, meaning a plot will feel "anchored" to a line of code just as naturally as a tooltip.

3. The "Quarto" Consolidation
Right now, you have to choose between Molten (execution), Jupytext (file format), and Image.nvim (rendering).

The Interim State: Setting this up feels like building a kit car. One update to a Lua dependency can break the whole chain.

The Improvement: The Quarto project is rapidly becoming the "VSCode of Neovim." It is an all-in-one ecosystem that wraps these tools. They are moving toward a single-install experience that handles the LSP, the kernel, and the preview window simultaneously.

Should you wait?
No, but manage your expectations. The "seamless" experience—where you open an .ipynb and it just works with zero config—is likely still a year away for Neovim. However, because you are on Arch/Hyprland, you are exactly the type of user these tools are built for.

My Advice:

If you want to be productive today: Use Jupynium. It gives you the Vim keys you love but uses the Browser (which is already "perfect" at rendering) as the display. It's the least "brittle" bridge.

If you want to live on the bleeding edge: Go with the Molten + Ghostty Sixel/Kitty setup. It will break occasionally, but when it works, it feels like you're living in the future.

